content:
The provided code chunk is part of a larger document that demonstrates how to set up a basic physics simulation using the Bullet physics engine in both Python and C++. Specifically, this chunk focuses on creating and configuring a static ground plane within the physics simulation. The process involves defining a collision shape for the ground (using `BulletPlaneShape`), attaching it to a rigid body node (`BulletRigidBodyNode`), positioning the node in 3D space, and finally adding it to the physics world. This is a fundamental step in setting up any physics-based environment where gravity and object interactions with the ground are required.

shape = BulletPlaneShape(Vec3(0, 0, 1), 1)

node = BulletRigidBodyNode('Ground')
node.addShape(shape)

np = render.attachNewNode(node)
np.setPos(0, 0, -2)

world.attachRigidBody(node)

cpp

...
PT(BulletPlaneShape) floor_shape = new BulletPlaneShape(LVecBase3(0, 0, 1), 1);
PT(BulletRigidBodyNode) floor_rigid_node = new BulletRigidBodyNode("Ground");

floor_rigid_node->add_shape(floor_shape);

NodePath np_ground = window->get_render().attach_new_node(floor_rigid_node);
np_ground.set_pos(0, 0, -2);
physics_world->attach(floor_rigid_node);
...

First we create a collision shape, in the case a BulletPlaneShape. We pass the plane's constant and normal vector within the shape's constructor. There is a separate page about setting up the various collision shapes offered by Bullet, so we won't go into more detail here.
